    "content": [
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Hard vs Soft Assignment"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "In k-means clustering, every point is assigned to exactly one cluster: the nearest centroid. This is a hard assignment — the membership vector is always a one-hot vector [0, 0, 1, 0, …]. A point exactly halfway between two clusters is still forced into one of them, with no way to represent the uncertainty."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "GMM soft clustering replaces hard membership with a probability distribution over clusters. Each point xn is assigned a responsibility vector [rn1, rn2, …, rnK] where rnk ∈ [0, 1] and Σk rnk = 1. A point in the overlap between two components might have r = [0.63, 0.37], expressing genuine uncertainty rather than forcing a binary choice."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "attrs": {
          "src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,",
          "alt": "Hard assignment forces every point into one cluster; soft assignment gives each point a probability vector over all clusters"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Computing and Using Soft Assignments"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The responsibility vector for a point is computed from the fitted GMM parameters using Bayes' rule (the E-step formula). Scikit-learn exposes both the soft probabilities and the hard argmax assignment through separate methods:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import numpy as np\nfrom sklearn.mixture import GaussianMixture\n\n# Synthetic 2-D data: two overlapping blobs\nrng = np.random.default_rng(7)\nX = np.vstack([\n    rng.multivariate_normal([0, 0], [[1.5, 0.3], [0.3, 1.0]], 200),\n    rng.multivariate_normal([3, 2], [[1.2, -0.2], [-0.2, 0.8]], 200),\n])\n\ngmm = GaussianMixture(n_components=2, covariance_type='full',\n                      n_init=5, random_state=0)\ngmm.fit(X)\n\n# Soft assignment: probability of belonging to each component\nprobs = gmm.predict_proba(X)   # shape (N, K) — each row sums to 1\nprint(\"First 5 responsibility vectors:\")\nprint(np.round(probs[:5], 3))\n# [[0.998 0.002]\n#  [0.001 0.999]\n#  [0.974 0.026]\n#  [0.993 0.007]\n#  [0.612 0.388]]  <- uncertain point near the boundary\n\n# Hard assignment: argmax of the probability vector\nlabels = gmm.predict(X)        # shape (N,)  — integer 0..K-1\nprint(\"Hard labels:\", labels[:5])\n# [0, 1, 0, 0, 0]\n\n# Log-probabilities for numerical precision on very confident points\nlog_probs = gmm.predict_proba(X)   # same; internally uses log-space\nentropy = -(probs * np.log(probs + 1e-300)).sum(axis=1)  # (N,)\nprint(f\"Mean assignment entropy: {entropy.mean():.3f} nats\")\n# Low entropy → confident; high entropy → uncertain"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "When Soft Assignments Matter"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Overlapping clusters:"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " When component distributions overlap significantly, many points are genuinely ambiguous. Soft assignments preserve this uncertainty rather than masking it."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Downstream probabilistic models:"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " A GMM can be used as the first stage in a pipeline. Passing the full responsibility vector (instead of a hard label) lets the next stage reason about cluster uncertainty."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Density estimation:"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " The GMM's primary use is as a density model, not just a clustering tool. Evaluating p(x) requires summing over all components with their mixing weights — soft assignment is the mechanism."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Anomaly detection:"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " A point with low responsibility under every component — max(rnk) is small — is an outlier that doesn't fit any cluster well. Soft assignments make this score continuous."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Uncertainty Quantification"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The entropy of the responsibility vector is a natural measure of assignment uncertainty for a single point:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockMath",
        "attrs": {
          "latex": "H_n = -\\sum_{k=1}^{K} r_{nk} \\ln r_{nk}"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Hn = 0 when the point is assigned entirely to one component (certain). Hn = ln K when responsibilities are uniform (maximum uncertainty). Points near cluster boundaries have high entropy; points deep inside a cluster have near-zero entropy."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import numpy as np\nfrom sklearn.mixture import GaussianMixture\n\ndef assignment_summary(X, gmm):\n    \"\"\"Print soft-assignment statistics for a fitted GMM.\"\"\"\n    probs = gmm.predict_proba(X)            # (N, K)\n    labels = gmm.predict(X)                 # (N,)\n    entropy = -(probs * np.log(probs + 1e-300)).sum(axis=1)  # (N,)\n    max_p = probs.max(axis=1)               # confidence in best cluster\n\n    print(f\"N points: {len(X)}, K components: {gmm.n_components}\")\n    print(f\"Max-prob mean: {max_p.mean():.3f}  (1.0 = always certain)\")\n    print(f\"Assignment entropy mean: {entropy.mean():.3f} nats\")\n    print(f\"  (max possible = ln K = {np.log(gmm.n_components):.3f})\")\n\n    # Identify the 5 most uncertain points\n    uncertain_idx = np.argsort(entropy)[-5:][::-1]\n    print(\"\\nTop-5 most uncertain points (highest entropy):\")\n    for i in uncertain_idx:\n        r = np.round(probs[i], 3)\n        print(f\"  x={np.round(X[i], 2)}, r={r}, H={entropy[i]:.3f}\")\n\nassignment_summary(X, gmm)"
          }
        ]
      },
